    "reasoning": "The goal is to implement Rule 90 cellular automaton for a 512-cell system, clocked by 'clk', and controlled by 'load'.\n\n1.  **Understand Rule 90:** The next state of a cell $q'[i]$ is the XOR of its two neighbors in the current state: $q'[i] = q[i-1] \text{ XOR } q[i+1]$.\n2.  **Boundary Conditions:** The boundaries are fixed at zero: $q[-1] = 0$ and $q[512] = 0$.\n3.  **Data Path:** The state $q$ is 512 bits wide, matching the input `data` width.\n4.  **Sequential Logic (Load/Update):** The system must update every clock cycle, but this update can be overridden by the `load` signal. We need a register (`current_q`) to hold the state $q$.\n    *   If `load` is high, `current_q` is loaded with `data`.\n    *   If `load` is low, `current_q` is updated using the Rule 90 calculation.\n5.  **Combinational Logic (Rule 90 Calculation):** We need to calculate the next state ($q_{next}$). For cell $i$ (from 0 to 511), $q_{next}[i] = q[i-1] \text{ XOR } q[i+1]$.\n    *   We must handle the boundary conditions explicitly:\n        *   For $i=0$: $q_{next}[0] = q[-1] \text{ XOR } q[1] = 0 \text{ XOR } q[1] = q[1]$.\n        *   For $i=511$: $q_{next}[511] = q[510] \text{ XOR } q[512] = q[510] \text{ XOR } 0 = q[510]$.\n        *   For $0 < i < 511$: $q_{next}[i] = q[i-1] \text{ XOR } q[i+1]$.\n6.  **Implementation Strategy:** Use a single `always @(posedge clk)` block for sequential updates. Inside this block, use an `if/else` structure controlled by `load`.\n7.  **Avoiding Syntax Errors:**\n    *   All signals are declared as `logic`.\n    *   The calculation of $q_{next}$ (which is derived from the *current* state $q$) must be done combinatorially before being assigned to the next state register.\n    *   We will use bit slicing and concatenation carefully. Since $q$ is the current state, we use $q$ to calculate $q_{next}$.\n\n**Detailed Calculation of $q_{next}$:**\nLet $q$ be the current state (the value in the register before the update).\n\n*   $q_{next}[0] = q[1]$ (since $q[-1]=0$)\n*   $q_{next}[1:510]$: This is a sequence of XORs. We can use slicing: $q[0:509] \text{ XOR } q[2:511]$.\n    *   $q[0:509]$ covers $q[i-1]$ for $i=1$ to $510$.\n    *   $q[2:511]$ covers $q[i+1]$ for $i=1$ to $510$.\n*   $q_{next}[511] = q[510]$ (since $q[512]=0$).\n\nCombining these into a single assignment for $q_{next}$ using concatenation or direct bit manipulation is most efficient. A simpler approach is to define $q_{next}$ piece by piece:\n\n1.  Initialize $q_{next}$ to all zeros.\n2.  $q_{next}[0] = q[1];\n3.  $q_{next}[511] = q[510];\n4.  For $i=1$ to $510$, $q_{next}[i] = q[i-1] \text{ XOR } q[i+1]$. This can be achieved by calculating the XOR sum of the shifted versions of $q$.\n\nLet $Q_{left} = q[0:509]$ (This is $q[i-1]$ for $i=1$ to $510$)\nLet $Q_{right} = q[2:511]$ (This is $q[i+1]$ for $i=1$ to $510$)\n\n$q_{next}[1:510] = Q_{left} \text{ XOR } Q_{right}$.\n\nThis structure is cleaner and avoids complex looping constructs in synthesis-friendly RTL.",
    "module": "module TopModule(input logic clk,\n    input logic load,\n    input logic [511:0] data,\n    output logic [511:0] q\n);\n\n    // Register to hold the current state of the cellular automaton\n    logic [511:0] current_q;\n\n    // Wire to hold the calculated next state (combinational result)\n    logic [511:0] next_q;\n\n    // Combinational logic for Rule 90 calculation\n    // q'[i] = q[i-1] XOR q[i+1]\n    always @* begin\n        // Initialize to zero as default state\n        next_q = 512'h0;\n\n        // Boundary condition i=0: q'[0] = q[-1] XOR q[1] = 0 XOR q[1] = q[1]\n        next_q[0] = current_q[1];\n\n        // Boundary condition i=511: q'[511] = q[510] XOR q[512] = q[510] XOR 0 = q[510]\n        next_q[511] = current_q[510];\n\n        // Interior cells i=1 to i=510: q'[i] = q[i-1] XOR q[i+1]\n        // q[i-1] corresponds to current_q[0:509] (shifted left by 1 bit)\n        // q[i+1] corresponds to current_q[2:511] (shifted right by 1 bit)\n        \n        // Using concatenation and XOR for the internal segment [1:510]\n        // current_q[0:509] is the left neighbor (q[i-1]) for i=1..510\n        // current_q[2:511] is the right neighbor (q[i+1]) for i=1..510\n        next_q[1:510] = (current_q[0:509] ^ current_q[2:511]);\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic: Update state on positive clock edge\n    always @(posedge clk)\n    begin\n        if (load) begin\n            // Load new data\n            current_q <= data;\n        end else begin\n            // Apply cellular automaton rule (Update)\n            current_q <= next_q;\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Output assignment\n    assign q = current_q;\n\nendmodule"
